column1: # Name, Affiliation, contact info: Andrew Nguyen, University of Vermont, PhD candidate, email - anbe642@gmail.com
# Financial support: National Science Foundation DEB Award # 1136644

#Methods and Data collection: Between 2014-2015, ant colonies within the genus Aphaenogaster  were collected from FL to Maine. We seearched Flat woods and mix hardwood habitats. These ants were allowed to acclimate at 25 C in a common garden experiment and were heat shocked in a slow ramping assay at 0.1C/min.

# Column explanations: n = numbering each row; Collection.date = date collected the colony; site = location of where colony was collected; state = State for which colony was collected; queen_status= QR is queenright and QL is queenless; lat= latitude in degrees decimals; lon = longitude in degrees decimals; genus= genus of ant; species= species of ant, includes outgroup; rad_seq_species = ddRAD-seq species designations; KO_temp_worker= Knock down temperature of ant, averaged among 4 individuals; colony.id= original names; colony.id2= more standardized names; Alt_names= more standardized labeling(SHC should be Lexington site); mean_ind_weight_mg= average weight of 4 individuals in mgs; habitat = specific habitat type; habitat_v2= simplified habitat type; nest.location = where ant colonies were found(simplified) ; collectors = who collected the colony, ANBE=Andrew Nguyen, KM= Katie Miller, MH= Mike Herrmann, SHC= Sara Helms Cahan, Lloyd Davis, LD= Lloyd Davis; HA= Heather Axen, tree_cover ranges from 0-100 percent got it from https://catalog.data.gov/dataset/nlcd-2011-percent-tree-canopy-cartographic
# Data layout and structure: Long format, Mostly everything is a factor except: lat, lon, KO_temp_worker, mean_ind_weight_mg, n--these are continuous variables
